column168: The Chief Mate discovered the leak from container SEAU172343-5 stowed in position 5-7-6 on hatch #5 of the Horizon Kodiak 928N.  The contents was eroding the foam insulation and causing some surface erosion on a couple of floor cross members on the ocean container.  The leak appeared to be small as it was only dripping on the vessel deck infrequently. The vessel Captain notified the vessel superintendent and safety manager.  A NRC Report was made with NRC case #1099986 and was later updated to number case #1100008 when the actual product was identified.  There were several acids in the container but it was difficult to determine which one was leaking.  We contacted an emergency response contractor who met the ship upon docking Sunday Morning at 6:00.  An assessment was made, the container was "diapered" and removed to the dock an positioned in a location to allow them to unload the shipment to determine the cause of the leak.  The vessel was decontaminated and neutralized to stop the activity of the sodium hydroxide.  The USCG observed the actions taken place.  The cause of the leak was abrasion on the drum which caused a pin hole leak.  This could possibly have been caused by loading a pallet next to the drum and sliding the pallet along the plastic packaging compromising its structure.  The cargo cleaned and neutralized and was transferred to another container.  The old container is being cleaned and may be put out of service due to the corrosion from the Sodium Hydroxide.
column169: Care should be taken during the loading and unloading operations to ensure that no packages are damaged.  The shipment did not show any signs of shifting.  Everything was intact.

column168: On November 3rd, 2014, FRA HazMat Inspector Vincent Au in the CSX Frontier Yard discovered TILX 316463, a loaded tank car of Petroleum Crude Oil leaking from around the manway, this due to a Less Than Tool Tight manway cover swing bolt. The car was isolated and the shipper was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2014-11-03-00076.  Michael Bethge, a CSX Hazardous Material Systems Manager, was dispatched to the scene and found manway cover swing bolt #6, 4 turns less than tool tight. The bolt was tightened to be tool tight, and the service nozzle was wipe-down.  Ms. Vicki Edblom, with DPTS Marketing,  LLC., office 763-452-1519 was notified of the situation found and the corrective action taken. TILX 316463 was released for transport.    This incident did NOT require a special move.    Cause Code: 200 (5 points)  NARRI: 5x(5+5+0)x(2+0) = 100

column168: The freight was found on damaged on the dock.  ERTS was contacted to have the spill cleaned up.

Dr 79301 reported 1 gallon spill into a containment area approximately 30 minutes into the unload at Castrol Industrial.  He said that the hose that was attached to his pump outlet got a hole in it.  He was standing by the control and was able to shut down immediately to minimize the spill.  Customer is handling clean up. He is waiting to see if someone can bring him another section of hose so he can complete the offload.    Driver said the hose looked okay when he hooked up.  He will bring it back to the OC for inspection, however it'll be hard to impossible to determine what caused the unseen hole to develop.  It could be from the wash process the tankwash used or simply degredation of the hose over time.     Spill didn't last longer than 30 minutes.
column169: All hoses are pressure tested annually and inspected at sustainment events as well as the driver prior to each delivery.  Knowing that the hole in the hose developed 30 minutes into the offload indicates the driver would not have been aware simply by looking.  There was no obvious signs of abrasion or damage from cleaning.  The driver followed the right process by remaining near the controls to shut down right away.  We will reinforce full inspections with him as well on all of his equipment to prevent leaks and spills.

column168: The Basin Western Truck and tank trailer were traveling East on HWY 21 approximately 3 miles from the Utah state line when driver veered off the right side causing truck and trailer to roll onto right side. The cargo tank did not rupture or fail, but the atmospheric equalization valve begin to leak resulting in an approximate 50 gallon loss. The driver of truck was able to minimize leaking with "plug and Dike" until another tank arrived at scene for cargo transfer. The majority of cargo was successfully transferred to another tank unit and delivered to specified destination. The release was contained to an 8' x 20' area and was covered until clean up efforts could begin.
column169: It was determined that driver fatigue played a part in this accident. It was reiterated to all Basin Western drivers the importance of not driving when feelings of fatigue are recognized. In addition all Basin Western drivers are being required to complete a defensive driving course. It is recommended that all drivers be made aware of their right and responsibility to stop work when conditions seem unsafe.

column168: On November 7, 2014, a 55-gallon drum containing UN1824 Sodium Hydroxide Solution was released from a faulty bung. The drum was located on a R&L Carriers trailer at the time of the release. Approximately eight ounces of product impacted the exterior of the drum and the trailer floor below. ERTS dispatched an environmental contractor to the site for response. The contractor replaced the bung and tested the drum. The impacted areas were neutralized and all waste was containerized for pending disposal.

The shipment was then loaded into a trailer destined to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.

column168: On Nov 11, 2014 at about 13:30, our driver swerved to miss another truck and rolled the tractor and tanker trailer.  The trailer was punctured in at least 4 places in the rollover and caused a spill of about 4000 gallons of Transmix (UN1203).  The puncture holes are from about 10" to 18" in diameter.  A burm was set up around the units to contain spill by TX DOT/DPS.  Another unit was brought in and pumped the remaining product off.  DCS Environmental has been called to do the clean-up.  Today, Nov 12, 2014, they are setting up the scene and expect excavation to start tomorrow.
column169: All drivers will be required to attend a safety meeting to go over the this accident.  They will be required to watch the "Tanker Rollover" video with discussion afterwards.

column62: Misaligned Material, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: On November 04, 2014 personnel in the CSXT Corbin Yard discovered WCHX 23125, a loaded tank car of Flammable Liquid, N.O.S. leaking from the top of the car.  The car was isolated and Domtar Paper Company LLC was notified via CHEMTREC Report # 2014-1104-00120.  HEPACO, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the manway cover gasket was misaligned, and the pressure relief device was broken and leaking.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shippers representative.  Contractor personnel installed a new manway nozzle gasket and secured the manway cover.  Contractor personnel then returned on a separate date and installed compliant pressure relief device.  The car will be released for transportation under a One Time Movement Approval so that it can moved to destination for offload; and subsequently moved to home shop for a bubble leak test.  A QA 7.1 will be filed.  This incident did require a special switching move.

column168: On November 11, 2014 while preparing to trans load a CMTV of UN2304 Naphthalene at the consignee location  a small amount of frozen product was observed at the internal valvle mounting. Operations were halted until extra response manpower could be mobilized in case of catastrophic failure. The area under the tanker was secured with absorbents and plastic sheeting, the flange was tightened in attempt to stop the leak, it did not complete stop the release so the area was heated with steam to assist with the product flow and the material was transferred successful. Approximately 5-10 gallons of product had been released and was contained and cleaned up for transport and disposal. QDI event # 43730

column168: A LOADER IN DOOR 210 DROPPED A HAZMAT PACKAGE APPROX 2.5-3FT TO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. LIQUID IMMEDIATELY STARTED COMING OUT OF THE BOX. HE LEFT THE TRAILER & NOTIFIED THE NEAREST SUPERVISOR. THE SUPERVISOR THEN CALLED THE DESIGNATED RESPONDERS WHEN I ARRIVED TO THE TRAILER, I UTILIZED MY DECISION TREE/RESPONSE SHEETS TO ASSESS THE SITUATION. I USED CLAY-BASED ABSORBENT TO BUILD A BARRIER AROUND THE LIQUID TO KEEP THE PUDDLE FROM SPREADING FARTHER. I PLACED THE LEAKING PACKAGE INTO A LINED SPILL TRAY. I PUT MORE CLAY-BASED ABSORBENT OVER THE LIQUID TO SOLIDIFY IT. I SWEPT ALL THE CONTAMINATED ABSORBENT & PLACED IT INTO ANOTHER LINED SPILL TRAY. SINCE THE FLOOR STILL APPEARED WET, 1 PUT SOME MORE CLAY-BASED ABSORBENT ON THE FLOOR. I THEN SWEPT UP THE CONTAMINATED ABSORBENT & ADDED IT TO THE SPILL TRAYS THEN I TOOK THE PACKAGE TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. WHEN I OPENED THE BOX, I SAW THAT 3 OF THE 4 GLASS BOTTLES HAD CRACKED/SHATTERED. THE 4TH WAS SOILED BY THE PRODUCT.

column168: On November 2, 2014, a Liquid Transport tanker trailer carrying UN1791 Sodium Hypochlorite solution was involved in a single vehicle accident that resulted in a rollover. As the result of the rollover, the tanker was damaged, releasing approximately 75-100 gallons of Sodium Hypochlorite solution to the roadway and a 5'x15' area of soil on the shoulder. Haz-tech Environmental responded out of Ripley, WV to assess, mitigate, and clean the release.The blacktop was completely cleaned, and the tanker trailer was up-righted and material transloaded prior to movement. Excavation of the impacted soil (approximately 10 tons) was completed on the day of the incident, and backfill was completed on 11/4/2014. All contaminated soils and absorbents were taken for pending disposal. The site was restored to its previous condition.

column168: On November 4, 2014, an R&L Carriers tractor trailer experienced a load shift that resulted in the release of approximately 1 cup of UN1992 Methyl Alcohol/Phenol. A 16 oz. plastic container was crushed within (1) 7 lb. box as the result of the load shift, and released 1 cup onto the trailer floor and other freight. No soils, drains or waterways were impacted as the release was contained to the trailer floor. Morgan Environmental responded out of Oakland, CA to properly clean the release and overpack the impacted freight utilizing necessary PPE. All contaminated and damaged freight was overpacked into (2) 5-gallon plastic pails for pending disposal. The pallet was re-stacked and the site was restored to its previous condition.

column168: At 2245 ET hours, Rosa Behn of R&l carriers contacted ERTS regarding the release of approximately 275 gallons of a UN2491 ETHANOLAMINE SOLUTION from a 275 gallon poly tote to the concrete floor at the New Carlisle, IN terminal. At the time of this report, no drains, soils or waterways were reported as being impacted. As required, ERTS notified the IDEM and Kirk acknowledged receipt of the incident and no RTN was issued at this time. ERTS has dispatched a network contractor ( SUNPRO-Elkhart, IN,) to respond. The contractor ETA to site is approximately 60 minutes. ERTS has requested copies of the BOL & MSDS. This incident may require a DOT5800. The caller indicated the tote was puncture by a fork lift operator during offloading. ERTS has reviewed the BOL and the released product is listed as a MARINE POLLUTANT. According to 49CFR171.15, the NRC must be notified of all releases over 119 gallons liquid. ERTS notified the NRC and Mr Threatt acknowledged receipt of the incident and issued RTN# 1101511

An R&L Carriers shipment of UN1760 Corrosive Liquid (Phosphoric & Nitric Acid) experienced a release on November 5, 2014. Approximately 7-8 gallons of material released from (1) 15-gallon poly DM as the result of a forklift puncture during loading operations. The release was contained to the trailer floor; no soils, drains or waterways were impacted. AES responded out of Belen, NM to neutralize the release with Sodium Bicarbonate solution and containerize all contaminated materials for pending disposal. The trailer floor was completely cleaned and the damaged drum was overpacked and taken for disposal. The site was restored to its previous condition.

column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE A STRONG ODOR AND WAS HELD FOR INVESTIGATION ON 11-5-14. THE FOLLOWING MORNING I RECEIVED A CALL FROM ONE OF THE DG PEOPLE. THEY HAD DISCOVERED THAT A METAL CAN OF PAINT COULD BE SEEN THROUGH THE SLIGHTLY OPEN CRATE. ALSO THERE WAS A BOX WHICH STATED AEROSOL CANS. I CONTACTED BOB BERGEN OF THE OKC/FAA BY PHONE & BY EMAIL TO ADVISE HIM OF THE INCIDENT AT 14:15 ON 11-6-2014. THE FOLLOWING DAY, I HAD NOT GOTTEN ANY VOICEMAIL OR EMAIL BACK FROM HIM, SO I CLALED GARY MOHR, THE SW REGION FAA MGR. BUT DID NOT HEAR FROM HIM. I THEN GOT A CALL FROM DAVID SCHAUFLER OF THE MKC/FAA ASKING ABOUT THIS SHIPMENT. WE DISCUSSED MY PREVIOUS CONVERSATIONS WITH THE SHIPPER. HE WAS ASKING IF HE COULD COME AND OPEN THE SHIPMENT AS HE HAD NOT PREPARED IT. HE CAME TO OUR RAMP LOCATION AND OPENED THE CRATE. THE AEROSOL BOX DID NOT HAVE ANY AEROSOL CANS IN IT AND ONLY CONTAINED 2 ALUMINUM DOWNSPOUTS. THERE NO DG INSIDE THAT BOX. HE THEN REMOVED THE LEAKING 1 GALLON CAN OF PAINT FROM THE CRATE. HE RE-SEALED THE CRATE AND IT WAS TO BE RELEASED SO IT COLD MOVE WITH THE REST OF HIS NON HAZARDOUS STUFF TO THE CONSIGNEE. NUMEROUS EMAILS WITH PHOTOS WERE LATER EXCHANGED WITH DAVID SCHAUFLER & WITH BOB BERGEN.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Broken Component or Device
column168: I wanted to provide a brief summary of the minor incident yesterday involving this car. Yesterday our Train Crew detected an odor coming from UTLX 200298, and made all appropriate notifications. The area was isolated, and KMX Chemical representatives responded from New Church, VA to asses. Upon arrival, they ascended the car with members from DNREC, and determined the car to be releasing a small amount of vapor with an inconsistent flow from multiple locations. These personnel found multiple hardware to be less than tool tight, as well as a bent vapor valve base and malfunctioning vacuum relief device. There efforts were able to slow the release, however not eliminate it completely. I therefore dispatched HEPACO-REACT, our Hazardous Materials Emergency Response Contractor to assist.     HEPACO-REACT provided photos (of which 3 are attached). The vacuum relief device was removed, and upon removal, found to be inoperable and in poor condition, and a solid plug was installed. The vapor valve was removed and found that the welded nipple on the valve assembly plate was bent, thus evidenced by leaning of the valve assembly. A solid plug was installed in its place. The liquid valve was removed, and found an inordinate amount of sealant putty / tape was used causing an ineffective seal. Those threads were cleaned, new sealant placed, and the valve was returned to proper orientation to include the plug.     Additionally, the man way was inspected and found 2 bolts to be less than tool tight, man way gasket was in good order. All man way cover bolts were returned to tool tight. The bottom outlet valve cap was found to be less than tool tight, and the gasket in poor condition. The gasket was replaced, and returned to tool tight.     At this point the car is secure and no longer leaking. Norfolk Southern will fulfill the FRA5800 reporting requirement. The next step is to have this car removed for repairs, which will require an OTMA. I ask that you copy me on those requests.
column169: No additional comments.

On November 10, 2014, at 0830 hours, Mechanical Foreman at the CSXT Parkersburg Yard, Parkersburg, West Virginia reported that  GATX 62613, a loaded tank car of UN1789, Hydrochloric Acid was venting. Reportedly there was a slight vapor cloud visible from the Vapor line at the PRV. The tank car was isolated. The consignee, Tetra Technologies, was notified directly to respond and assist in securing the release. The shipper Arkema was notified via Chemtrec, report #2014-1110-00035 . Ron Anderson 304 488 5419 from Tetra Technologies was dispatched to the Parkersburg Yard. Ron Anderson found that the PRV was in fact releasing vapor due to a blown frangible disk. The frangible disk was replaced and the release was thus secured. GATX 62613 was then placed back in transportation. This incident did not require a special move. column168: When conducting a TAG (The Adherence Group) inspection to confirm container contents against the bill of lading, TAG discovered one carton of class 2.1 Aerosols marked with "Limited Quantity" markings that was not declared as hazardous on the dangerous goods declaration.  The shipment was placed on hold.  The shipper was contacted and provided a corrected bill of lading.  There was other hazardous cargo, even class 2.2 cargo, in the container that was properly declared on the hazmat declaration.  It seems that the shipper missed this carton.  This may be due to the domestic road leg of the shipment that did not require hazmat shipping papers.  The shipper failed to declare the shipment for the domestic water leg of the transportation chain.
column169: Package markings need to be compared with the shipping papers and mode of transportation to ensure compliance.

On November 18, 2014 at approximately 10:30 personnel in the CSXT Cumberland Yard were notified by FRA HazMat Inspector that he had discovered PROX 40461, a loaded tank car of combustible liquid diesel fuel leaking from the manway on the car. The car was moved to the diesel unloading rack. The shipper CSX Tranflo, and local, state and/or federal agencies as applicable were notified. SPSI, a CSXT response contractor was dispatched to the scene and found a bad manway cover bolt that will not stay tight on the car and a questionable manway cover gasket. Contractor personnel replaced gasket with a manway nozzle style gasket and the car leasee was notified to have a mobile repair company replace the manway bolt. the car was wiped off and held pending the manway bolt being fixed.      This incident did not require a special switching move.   This incident does not require a 7.1    NARRI= 200   5X(5+1+0)X(2+0)=60

column168: On 11/13/2014 at 0930, Rochester & Southern Car Inspector Tim Hudson noted on his inspection of a newly arrived train that SBLX 24269 had product stain on the top of the car around the fill hole, he immediately went to get a drip pan so that no product would hit the ground. He then made notifications to company personal, the DOT of NY and Arch Chemicals. Arch Chemicals contacted Olin Chemicals Emergency Action and they were activated at 0955 arriving at the scene at 1400 hrs. Olin Chemical inspected SBLX 24269 for vandalism and defects not taking exceptions to anything, they renewed the fill hole gasket, air tested the car at a pressure of 40lbs. they wiped the product off of the outside of the car and took all cleaning product was taken away by Olin Chemical.
column169: I suggested to Arch Chemical and Olin Chemical to possibly do more inspections of there gaskets when loading and unloading of tank cars.

column168: On November 10, 2014, a CEVA Logistics model 406 tanker trailer struck a sign post during transit which consequently punctured the body of the tanker. As a result of the puncture, approximately 5,600 gallons of NA1993 Combustible fuel oil (diesel fuel) was released onto the soil & gravel at the CSX railyard and into a nearby retention pond. As a response, Hulls Environmental and ERS were dispatched to the scene to mitigate the release impact and prevent further migration of the fuel. Arcadis was also dispatched by CSX Railyard personnel to assist with on-scene project management. All contaminated soils and waters were removed from the ground within a 3-day period. All waste is currently pending characterization and final disposal. The site was back-filled and restored to its previous condition.

column168: On November 10, 2014, a 55-gallon steel drum of UN1897 Tetrachloroethylene released approximately 3-4 oz. of material as the result of an apparent pinhole puncture or seam malfunction at an R&L Carrier terminal dock in Elgin, IL. No soils, drains or waterways were impacted by the minimal release. HazChem responded out of Addison, IL to overpack the damaged container and clean the release. All contaminated absorbents were containerized for disposal. The drum was overpacked and the site was restored to its previous condition.
Driver put loading pump in the wrong direction causing a 5 gallon spill of crude oil.

Upon arrival at the destination terminal, 1 drum was found leaking. Upon further investigation, it appears that the body of the drum had a small crack and was leaking material into the trailer. The drum was immediately placed into an over pack along with the cleanup materials. Due to the hazard of material, package specifications were not able to be obtained.
column169: Closer inspection of drums by the shipper could have prevented this spill.

column169: Adequate blocking and bracing of freight would have prevented this material release. Future dock employee meeting topics will include additional information on the importance of blocking and bracing freight.

UPS info as follows:    UPS Tracking # 1Z 941 162 03 4871 9257    Shipper:   R.S. Hughes Company Inc.  7031 South 193rd street  Kent, WA  98032    Consignee:  311 1st  Avenue  Wrangell, AK 99929

VEHICLE TRAVELING NORTHBOUND ON HWY 191 (WYOMING). VEHICLE TRAILER RIGHT WHEELS WENT OFF ROAD ONTO SOFT SHOULDER. DRIVER OVER CORRECTED RESULTING OVER TURN OF TRAILER. TRAILER BREACHED AND RELEASED DIESEL FUEL. RESPONDERS BUILT DAM TO CONTAIN FUEL. TOW TRUCK UPRIGHTED TRAILER AND TEMPORARILY STOPPED LEAK. REMAINING FUEL WAS OFF-LOADED TO SECOND TRUCK DISPATCHED BY CARRIER (RED HORSE OIL). RED HORSE OIL SUCKED UP POOLED DIESEL FUEL. HOLE IN BACK COMPARTMENT OF TRAILER ABOUT 2"X10". OTHER COMPARTMENTS 1/2" DIAMETER HOLES.
column169: DRIVERS HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO LOAD TRAILERS FOR MINIMAL "SLOSH", EFFECT. AND, TO ADJUST SLOWLY SHOULD AN EVENT REQUIRING CORRECTIVE STEERING TAKE PLACE. DRIVERS WERE REMINDED OF THE HIGH CENTER OF GRAVITY WITH TANKERS AND IMPACT OF FLUIDS MOVING DURING TRANSIT. FURHTER, DRIVERS WERE REMINDED (WITH SIGNIFICANT EMPHASIS) OF THE HAZARDS ASSOCIATED WITH TRANPORTING FUELS BOTH FROM A DANGER AND ENVIRONMENTAL STAND POINT.    DRIVERS HAVE BEEN ADVISED TO "SLOW DOWN" AND FOCUS ON ACCURACY AND SAFETY.

column62: Missing Component or Device; Valve Open
column168: A FRA inspector reported entrained tank car GBRX 701027 that recently arrived at the consignee's unloading tracks with commodity spillage on the right side of its tank shell and trucks. The consignee's unloading service provider (Savage Services) inspection of GBRX 701027 revealed its liquid valve was open and this valve's closure plug not applied.  The liquid valve was closed and its closure plug was applied to a tool tight condition. The shipper seal at the protective housing cover (Allied 1585186) was reported intact. Also noted was commodity spray on four entrained tank cars that trailed GBRX 701027. Savage Services indicated that they would clean the commodity spillage from GBRX 701027 and the other tank cars found with sprayed commodity. The outage in GBRX 701027 was gauged to estimate the possible commodity loss during transportation. No reports of commodity spillage along the routed BNSF right of way have been noted.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Norfolk Southern personnel reported the odor of styrene around CGTX26322.  Upon inspection by a contractor, the source of the odor was found to be the cam-lock fitting on the vapor line.  The release of vapor was the result of a deteriorated gasket.
column169: Shipper must properly inspect all gaskets prior to offering container for transportation.

column168: CN Transportation department employee noted product coming from the top of tank car UTLX 11439 (L / Sulfuric Acid, Spent, UN1832) during switching operations at the CN McComb Yard, McComb, MS. All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated. CN's response team responded noting liquid coming from the liquid line cap.  The pressure was relieved from the tank car and the leak stopped.  The liquid line cap was checked for tightness.  An additional half turn was achieved on the liquid line cap.  The leak was secured.  Railcar was released to destination.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: Tank car FURX 130159 in the railyard was reported with commodity on its side shell that emanated from its manway closure. Contract responders inspecting FURX 130159 reported the shipper seal numbered 6124608 was intact at the manway closure. Responders found 1 of 6 manway securement eyebolt nuts not tool tight. The installed manway cover gasket was in place in the gasket groove and appeared serviceable. Responders installed a new manway nozzle gasket to ensure a tight seal. The manway cover was then closed and properly secured. The small amount of non-evaporated spillage on FURX 130159 was wiped.     The side qualification stencil on FURX 130159 indicated that its last tank qualification was in 2012.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Tank car NATX 303762 was reported dripping commodity from its bottom outlet valve while in the railyard. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders immediately inspected NATX 303762 and reported finding the bottom outlet valve's (BOV) operating handle not pinned closed which allowed the operating handle to drop downward into an open position. The responders moved the BOV's operating handle to its closed position and secured it with 'zip' ties since the pinning mechanism was missing. Afterwards, the dripping commodity from around the bottom outlets cap's (BOC) threaded connection ceased. The BOC was checked for tool tightness and it was reported tool tight. All spillage evaporated.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

Norfolk Southern personnel reported a rotten egg odor near tank car TILX180141.  Upon inspection by a contractor, it was determined the odor was the result of a release of product on top of the tank car from the tell-tale valve on the external relief valve.  The rupture disc below the relief valve had apparently ruptured and the tell-tale valve had been left in the open position.
column169: Shipper must properly inspect all valves and fittings before car is released for transportation.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: Driver was traveling westbound on US Hwy 82 in Mathiston, MS when he observed a motorist flashing his lights. Driver then observed a mist behind him and pulled off on to the north shoulder of Hwy 82. Driver observed the front pressure relief valve in the top of the trailer leaking vapor into the atmospher. Driver notified the company and the local police department arrived immediately after. The police officer notified the fire department. The local news reported approximately 250 people were evacuated. The vent did not reseat and continued to leak until the trailer was transloaded. It was discovered that the front baffel welds had detached and the baffel was hitting the pressure relief valve.
column169: Recommend respositioning the baffel so if the welds break the baffel will not come in contact with the valve. Also redesign the baffel mounts in the trailer.

column168: On November 5, 2014, Landstar (Inway) contacted ERTS regarding a 30 gallon "UN2922 Chromium Trioxide" release at a customer location, "Chemetall Oakite"; 1100 Technology Drive, Jackson, MI. It was reported that the driver of a Landstar Inway tractor (420072) trailer (689108) arrived at the customer location and discovered a liquid release coming from the trailer, trailing down the street and into the customer parking area. The root cause of the release was due to a load shift. The shift in the trailer caused a hook in the ratchet strap to puncture the side of the 275 gallon tote, consequently releasing the material to the trailer floor and roadway. ERTS dispatched a network contractor to the site for response and remediation activities.

During a BNSF outbound train inspection in the railyard, entrained tank car UTLX 110059 was reported with a thin trail of liquid commodity on its upper side shell that emanated from its manway area. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders inspected UTLX 110059 and reported that commodity was expelled from the threaded vacuum relief valve (VRV) that was installed on UTLX 110059's manway cover. Responders neutralized the spillage on UTLX 110059 with baking soda and water rinsed the neutralized spill area. No ground impact from spillage was observed. UTLX 110059 was carefully set-out from its train and isolated in the railyard. On 11/18/2014, BNSF responders removed the malfunctioning VRV and a 2 1/2 inch pipe plug was secured in the VRV's vacated orifice.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 11/4/14 at approx. 1635, company transport driver was traveling East on HWY 302 East of Kemit, Texas traveling at approx. 71 mph in wet/rainy conditions. As the driver entered a curve in the road,the truck struck a body of water and hydroplaned which caused the driver to lose control of the vehicle.  While out of control, the truck rotated 180 degrees, crossed the oncoming traffic lane and overturned onto it's passenger side coming to rest facing West.
column169: Investigation concluded that the driver was using cruise control in adverse weather conditions. This directly contributed to the loss of control of the vehicle. Enhance driver training on the use of cruise control and the effects of adverse weather conditions.

column168: ON 11/18/2014 AT 0720 DURING AN INBOUND INSPECTION AT B & P FACILITY IN WARREN PA. THE CAR INSPECTOR NOTED THAT THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP OF SMXX 46159 HAD WET PRODUCT ON IT. AFTER OBSERVING THE CAR HE NOTED NO PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE CAR, AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE HE IMMEDIATELY WENT AND GOT A FIVE GALLON BUCKET, SECURED IT TO THE CAR AND THEN HAD THE CREW PLACE IT ON A SECURE TRACK WHERE IT WAS TIED DOWN AND FLAGGED OUT. HE THEN NOTIFIED VP MECHANICAL OFFICER GENE EVANS AND FRA INSPECTOR TIM ROWAN. THEN THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED SO THEY COULD TAKE APPROPRIATE MEASURES TO HAVE THE CAR REPAIRED. RON GOULD FROM HEPACO REACT LLC. WAS CONTACTED TO MAKE REPAIRS SO THE CAR COULD BE MOVED TO ITS FINAL DESTINATION, UNITED REFINERY WARREN, PA. NOTE: FAILURE WAS DUE TO DETERIORATED PACKING AND GASKET.
column169: THIS WAS THE SECOND TIME, ONE WEEK TO THE DAY, THAT THE SAME INCIDENT OCCURRED WITH THE SAME SERIES OF CARS. AFTER TALKING TO THE SHIPPER HE STRESSED HIS CONCERN WITH THIS ISSUE AND STATED HE WAS NOT USING THESE SERIES OF CARS TO SHIP HIS PRODUCT ANYMORE.  I THEN CONTACT THE LOCAL FRA INSPECTOR TIM ROWAN. WITH THE INFORMATION ABOUT THE FAILURES OF THE CAR, I ASKED IF SHIPPERS HAD TO VERIFY THE CAR OR CARS THAT THEY COULD HANDLE THE PRODUCT THEY WERE HANDLING, HE STATED THERE ARE NO FRA MANDATES ON THIS.  SUGGESTION WOULD BE: ONE WOULD THINK THAT ALL SAFETY MEASURES WOULD BE TAKEN THAT ANY CAR COULD HANDLE THE PRODUCT IT WAS HAULING.

column168: CN Transportation Department employee noted product coming from the top of tank car UTLX 70772 (L / Combustible Liquid, N.O.S. Fuel Oil, NA1993) during switching operations at the CN Destrehan Yard, Destrehan, LA. All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated. CN's response team responded noting liquid coming from the top of the railcar.  Upon inspection, the leak was coming from the vacuum relief device. The manway was opened to inspect the valve seat of the vacuum relief device. Debris was found to be in the o-ring seat. The debris was removed from the relief device. The leak was secured. Tank car was released for movement to destination.

column168: On November 19, 2014, an R&L Carriers tractor trailer experienced a load shift that resulted in the release of approximately 15 gallons of UN2874 Furfuryl Alcohol from (1) 55-gallon steel drum. The drum was punctured as a result of the shift due to inadequate preparation for transport. No soils, drains or waterways were impacted as a result of this release, as all material lost was contained to the trailer floor and asphalt below. SWS responded out of Greensboro, NC to clean the release and overpack the damaged drum. Trailer floor and asphalt were completely cleaned and waste was taken via SWS for pending disposal. The site was restored to its previous condition.

A 60 gallon poly drum was found in a trailer on its side due to improper blocking and bracing. The fall resulted in two small puncture holes in the drum that released approximately 10 gallons of material to the trailer floor. Once the drum was discovered it was overpacked and the released material neutralized and cleaned.

A BNSF road switcher derailed three loaded covered hoppers on the mainline yard lead. Cause of this derailment was attributed to a broken rail. A three compartment covered hopper FURX 829014 that derailed on its side released commodity from its damaged A-end bottom discharge outlet structure. The A-end of FURX 829014 was covered with a plastic tarp at the derailment site and is awaiting commodity removal with appropriate disposal afterwards. Spilled material was excavated, placed into roll-off boxes, profiled and earmarked for appropriate disposal. Soil sampling was initiated.

column168: Carrier at consignee to off load, carrier and consignee employee hooked up everything properly, carrier started pump, consignee employee said the hose blew and carrier shut down the pump. Consignee employee said the hose was constricted at the end connection to the pipe and blew the coupler fitting causing 10-20 gallons to spill. Consignee is cleaning the spill area with pads that absorbs the product from the water (dyke system). Carrier and consignee used a spare hose and was able to complete offloading with no futher issues. Consignee has taken all the hoses out of service for inspection. All off loading is done with consignee hoses. Event 43845

column168: When the shipping tech put the nitrogen on the rail car to unload it, the cars pressure relief device opened, releasing a minimum amount of nitrogen. The shipping tech called the safety specialist to investigate and he went to the rail car. The shipping tech demonstrated what was happening and I advise him to not unload the car. About a 1/4 lb of nitrogen was released . The rail car is owned by Dow Chemical. We called Dow, who told us to call Chemtrec and report the incident.After the report was made to Chemtrec, Dow contacted us and informed us that they were sending their in the field repair contractors to repair the pressure relief device. USES came onto our site and was able to fix a worn gasket that wasn't allowing the pressure relief device to seat properly. We then unloaded the car with no further problems
column169: We will be filling a complaint with Dow to fix their issues with the gaskets

column168: ON NOVEMBER 12, 2014 I RECEIVED A CALL FROM CONDUCTOR CHRIS HILL ABOUT A POTENTIAL LEAK COMING FROM ECUX 575055. ECUX 575055, A LOADED BUTADIENES CAR STORED FOR EXXONMOBIL WAS LOCATED IN MOSS POINT NORTH YARD WHERE THE CREW WAS PERFORMING SWITCHING OPERATIONS. I IMMEDIATELY LEFT THE OFFICE TO INSPECT THE CAR AND BEGAN MAKING CONTACT WITH THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, MISSISSIPPI EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY, CHEMTREX, DEQ, JACKSON COUTNY SHERIFF'S DEPT., MOSS POINT POLICE DEPARTMENT, JACKSON COUNTY FIRE CHIEF, AND EXXONMOBIL. UPON INSPECTION I COULD NOT PIN POINT THE EXACT ORIGIN OF THE LEAK, BUT I DID NOTICE A FAINT ODOR IN THE AREA.  I INFORMED EVERYONE THAT THE CAR WAS BEING CLOSELY MONITORED AND CORDONED OFF UNTIL A QUALIFIED HAZMAT SPECIALIST COULD INSPECT THE CAR. BRAD RATLIFF FROM DEQ SAID THAT THEY WOULD NOT BE COMING DOWN TO INPSECT THE CAR UNLESS THERE WAS A STRONG INDICATION OF A LEAK. CHRISTOPHER EDMONDS INFORMED ME AT 18:00 CDT THAT EXXONMOBIL WOULD BE SENDING A RESCAR OUT ON NOVEMBER 13TH. I CALLED MY RELIEF BRANDON JOHNSON AND GAVE HIM ALL NECESSARY DETAILS OF THE POSSIBLE LEAK ALONG WITH ALL OF THE CONTACT INFORMATION. ONE OF THE LIQUID VALVES WAS LEFT LOOSE ALONG WITH A PLUG.  RESCAR CAME IN TIGHTENED THE VALVE BUT DID NOT CHECK THE PLUG. LATER OMI REPRESENTATIVE FRANK PIEDISCALZO WAS SENT OUT TO CHECK THE PROBLEM HE DID NOT DETECT ANY LEAK. HE DID TIGHTEN VALVE AND PLUG AND THE BAGGED THE VALVE AND PLUG OVERNIGHT, CAME BACK NEXT MORNING AND NO LEAK WAS DETECTED. CAR WAS DEEMED GOOD WITH NO DEFECTS.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column168: 11/5/2014: At approximately 830AM, while observing CSX train C759/04 arriving in Conrail's Pavonia Yard, Camden, NJ, Yardmaster G. McNelia noted product leaking from the top of tank car UTLX 662595, load, Environmentally Hazardous Substances, Liquid, NOS (Alcohol C12-C15 Poly 1-6 Ethoxylate) at the top of the car.    Car was set out to an accessible location in the yard.  Conrail's A. Richter, Risk Management notified by Manager Field Operations R. Keating.  Conrail emergency response contractor, Hepaco, contacted to respond and remediate.    Further inspection by Hepaco personnel revealed the manway cover gasket was deteriorated.  Gasket replaced by manway nozzle boot gasket of compatible material with the product, and manway cover was resecured and sealed.  Car was moved to the Car Shop area where it was later decontaminated of spilled product on the sides of the car.  Car okayed for forwarding to original destination.  No product on the ground noted.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: Tank car UTLX 206580 was reported expelling commodity from its top fitting area during switching operations in the railyard. UTLX 206580 was isolated in the railyard for a detailed inspection. The spillage on UTLX 206580's side shell mostly evaporated and no ground impact from the spillage was observed. Contract responders inspecting UTLX 206580 reported the source of the commodity release was from its reclosing 165 psig pressure relief valve (PRV).  The PRV was suspected of incurring either a broken stem or spring. The PRV was not removed to verify the cause of failure. The responders inserted wedges to gag off the PRV preventing any further commodity release. Non-evaporated spillage was wiped. UTLX 206580 is awaiting a replacement PRV.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: Tanker trucks are loaded with crude oil in San Ardo.  The shell capacity of the tanker trucks is 200bbls but their weight limitations on the road prevent them from taking a full 200bbl load.  Operators at San Ardo were loading 162bbls of crude oil onto a tanker truck.  When the meter reached approximately 155bbls, the operator saw crude oil coming out of the vapor vent pipe.  Approximately 7.8 gallons of crude oil flowed down the vent pipe and reached the surrounding soil.
column169: The driver of the truck new that he was supposed to check his weight tickets to ensure that his truck was empty but he did not.Tanker trucks are loaded with crude oil in San Ardo.      Procedure at the time of the incident counted on the driver reviewing his paperwork (weight tickets and meter tickets) to confirm that his truck was empty then verbally conveying that to the EMPCo. operator instead of the EMPCo. operator reviewing the paperwork and confirming first hand that the truck was indeed empty.

column168: On November 25, 2014, a Key Energy Services 406 tanker trailer experienced a fuel overfill during unloading operations, releasing approximately 80-100 gallons of NA1993 Diesel fuel to the surrounding soil at a fuel island in Carthage, TX. No drains or waterways were impacted as the result of this release. ES&H responded out of Bossier City, LA to clean the release, remove all standing fuel pools, and excavate the diesel-impacted soils. All contaminated soils were excavated and transported for pending disposal. Confirmatory samples were taken to ensure that the site was remediated to TX state standards. The site was restored to its original condition.

column168: Driver of the gasoline transport, hooked up his drop hose to the 92 octane tank.  the collar, later to be found that it was worn out, did not properly connect to the end of the drop hose. When the driver opened up the unloading valve at the tanker, the end of the hose slipped off the collar, causing the spill.  The driver set out absorbent pads to stop the spread of gasoline, and the fire department was called to help contain the leak.  The fire department used 8 bags of floor dry and 30, 18 inch absorbent pads to fully clean up the spill.

column168: On November 17, 2014 at 0850 CT, two 55-gallon drums containing UN1993 Paraffin Corrosion Inhibitor were dropped off of a flat-bed tractor trailer on I-35 NB near exit 59 in Fort-Worth, TX, due to inadequate blocking and bracing. column168: A FRA inspector reported DBUX 300330 in the railyard with commodity on its side shell that emanated from its manway closure area. Contract responders inspected DBUX 300330 and reported that the manway gasket installed in the manway cover gasket groove appeared deteriorated and not providing a good closure seal.  This manway lid gasket was removed and the gasket sealing surfaces were cleaned. A new manway nozzle gasket was installed and the manway closure was re-secured. Spillage on DBUX 300330's side shell was wiped. No ground impact from spillage was observed. Intact shipper seal at the manway closure numbered 667613 was replaced by seal numbered 1113056. Response was concluded by 1430 hrs. PST, 11/18/2014.    Per side qualification stencil: Tank Qualified 2013 Due 2023
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: On November 28, 2014,  Mechanical Foreman at the CSXT Parsons Yard, Columbus, Ohio was informed that FRA Hazardous Material Inspector took exception to GATX 205820, a loaded tank car of UN2078, Toluene Disocyanate had solidified product on the exterior of the tank car with no material released on the ground. The release was reported on November 28, 2014 at 09:35. The shipper, Bayer Materialscience, was notified via Chemtrec, report #2014-1128-00022. Specialized Professional Services Inc. SPSI, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the Parsons Yard. SPSI found that the material released from an improperly secured liquid line that was less than tool tight at the threads beneath the valve. The shipper representative, Chad Blake, 304-281-4864 was notified of the situation found. The material was removed from the valve and exterior of the tank car and then securely tightened. The valve handle was bent to allow the closure of the breadbox. GATX 205820 is currently on hold pending receipt of one time movement approval to continue in transportation.    This incident require a special move.  NARRI: 5x(5+5+0)x(2+0) = 100  Cause code:282

column168: A BNSF train was stopped on the main track after being alerted to a possible wheel defect on an entrained railcar. BNSF mechanical responders inspecting this stopped train observed entrained tank car NATX 303479 with a slow commodity drip emanating from its closed bottom operated bottom outlet valve (BOV). Responders tightened the BOV's packing nut at the BOV valve stem which ended the slow drip from the BOV valve stem. All other bottom fittings on NATX 303479 were secure and all spillage evaporated.

column168: During delivery operations, 1-55 gallon steel drum of UN1987 Trichloroethylene was punctured by other freight and released it's contents to the trailer floor, gravel roadway, asphalt roadway and impacted a drain at the delivery facility.A contractor was dispatched and cleaned up the impacted areas and staged all waste on site for pending disposal activities. The RQ for the material was 100 pounds and all regulatory bodies were notified.

ON 11/11/2014, R&L Carriers personnel reported that one drum of UN1814 Potassium Hydroxide Solution was punctured by a forklift in the back of the trailer and released approximately 30 gallons to the trailer floor. ERTS dispatched a contractor to the site for response and remediation activities.

column14: CSX RAIL YARD AT 500 TAYLOR ST
column168: A GREAT LAKES PETRO/CONSUMERS PETRO FUEL TRUCK DRIVER WAS DELIVERING DIESEL FUEL TO A CSX TRAIN AT THE YARD IN CAYSE, SC ON 11/24/14. FUEL WAS DISCOVERED ON THE GROUND AFTER THE FILL. IT IS UNKNOWN WHAT THE ACTUAL CAUSE OF THE SPILL WAS. IT IS ANTICIPATED THAT THE GAUGING DEVICE ON THE TRAIN WAS NOT ACCURATE AND THE DRIVER MAY HAVE ACCIDENTALLY OVERFILLED THE TANK AND APPROXIMATELY 50-100 GALLONS OF FUEL WAS SPILLED ON THE GROUND NEAR THE TRACKS. SOME OF THE FUEL DID REACH A DITCH/DRAIN BUT WAS REMOVED. THE INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO THE STATE (SDCHEC) AND LOCAL POLICE/FIRE. GREAT LAKES PETRO'S FLEET SAFETY MANAGER, CSX AND OUR SPILL RESPONDER (HEPACO) WERE AT THE SCENE AND OVERSAW CLEANUP OF THE SPILL. CONTAMINATED SOIL AND GRAVEL WAS EXCAVATED. FOLLOW UP TESTING AND REPORTS WILL BE CONDUCTED ACCORDING TO STATE LAW TO ENSURE NO FURTHER ACTION IS NEEDED.
column169: THE DRIVER RESPONSIBLE FOR THE INCIDENT WILL RECEIVE ADDITIONAL TRAINING ON HOW TO PROPERLY GAUGE/CONFRIM FUEL AMOUNTS AND HOW TO PREVENT A SPILL. WE WILL ALSO INVESTIGATE USING A NEW FUEL NOZZLE THAT SHUTS OFF WHEN TANKS ARE FULL.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column62: Defective Component or Device; Deterioration or Aging
column168: Tank car UTLX 205659 was reported in the railyard with commodity on its side shell. Initial inspection of UTLX 205659 by a BNSF mechanical responder revealed that the spillage source emanated from a 4 bolt blind flange secured onto the valve fitting plate/pressure plate assembly. UTLX 205659 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard. On 11/21/2014, contract responders inspected the bolted blind flange connection. All four flange bolt nuts were tool tight. The gasket under the flange plate was inspected. The gasket appeared old and degraded and it was removed. A new gasket was fitted and the blind flange plate was re-installed and properly secured.  The spillage on the side shell of UTLX 205659 and around the valve housing area was wiped. No ground impact from spillage was reported.   On 11/24/2014, the same contract responders pressure tested the flange connection securement by inserting nitrogen gas into UTLX 205659 and no leaks were detected.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 11/30/2014, at 09:51, train Q60928 derailed 18 cars, 7 hazmat cars including GATX 72016. During the damage assesment CSX personnel discovered GATX 72016 had a minor release in the amount of approximately one pint . This car is a loaded tank car of Phosphoric Acid Solution, leaking from manway. The car was isolated and the shipper PCS Sales, Chemtrec, NRC and local fire department were notified.  CHEMTREC Report # 2014-11-30-00024. SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor and CSX Hazardous Materials Manager Chris Machenberg, were on scene and found one manway bolt loose and a cut manway gasket. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Tracey Smith 847-208-2727 . Contractor personnel secured the manway and decontaminated the car, car was involved in the derailemnt and will be transfered in the field because of damages to the railcar. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 required is not required.    Cause Code:208  NARRI:5(5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80
column169: No additional comments.

column168: Tank car CTCX 733042 in the railyard was reported with commodity on its side shell that appeared to emanate from its manway closure. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected CTCX 733042 and reported all six manway securement eyebolts were not applied and hanging downward. No shipper seal was found at the manway closure. The responder applied the eyebolts and secured the manway closure. CTCX 733042 was moved and isolated in the railyard for cleaning by contract responders. On 11/29/2014 contract responders re-inspected CTCX 733042 prior to cleaning commodity from its side shell. The outage within CTCX 733042 was measured. The responders installed a new manway nozzle gasket. The manway closure was properly secured ensuring all securement eyebolts were in a tool tight condition. Seal numbered 827329 was applied at the manway closure. All other valves and fittings were found secure. The spillage on CTCX 7330420 was treated with a biodegradable detergent and wiped. No ground spillage was observed at the site.  The outage in CTCX 733042 that was gauged was used to calculate an estimate of possible commodity loss during transportation. No reports of commodity spillage along the BNSF routed right of way have been noted.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: driver was reaching for his lunch box and when he did, the right front steer tire dropped of the pavement (approx.4"-6" drop) and onto the soft shoulder of rte 25 West in Porter, Maine; the shoulder gave way and the tractor tires dropped an additional 12"-15" casing the tractor and trailer to go into the ditch and to roll over onto it's side; when the trailer rolled over, the side of the trailer made contact with the side of the ditch causing an 8" gash in pocket #5 (2,500 gallon pocket), and another 24" gash in the vapor rail of pocket #1 (3,500 gallon pocket); these gashes allowed approx.2,240 gallons of gasoline to leak out of pocket #5, and approx. 160 gallons of gasoline out of pocket #1.Product loss was verified after pumping product from rolled trailer into another trailer with equal size pockets, the pockets were then stuck for inch readings and readings were compared to the tank chart for that trailer.
column169: Re-educate drivers on distracted driving, use this incident as an example of what can happen when distracted, have additional driver safety meetings and use the driver that was involved in the accident as a speaker to explain what happened, and why it happened. Make distracted driving a focal point at water cooler and tool box talks.

column168: On 11/19/2014 the driver's tank gage was broken and replaced. The replacement included the entire valve assembly with a new gage-arm. It was determined that the old tank gage had broken at the elbow of the gage arm inside the truck's tank. Subsequently, the arm no longer attached fell to the bottom of the bob-tail's tank. Consequently, when the driver began to unload, the broken gage arm migrated to the open valve due to the force imparted by draining the tank via gravity flow.The broken arm was lodged inside the valve preventing the driver to place the valve in the close position.Upon further inspection the mechanics found the tip of the gage-arm had wedged the valve in the OPEN position. Consequently, 10 gallons of produced water was released.
column169: This truck was originally configured with no loading/unloading valve after the DOT valve. The piping will be reconfigured with redundant valves to prevent future releases.

They started to gravity feed the container while they continued to work on the pump switch. The pump suddenly came on and a few minutes later the container started to over flow.Terminal personnel used absorbent materials to clean up the spill.
column169: Terminal personnel should insure that all loading equipment is working properly before the loading process is begun.

column168: On November 18, 2014, during the examination of export documents offered for transport. The carrier (Seaboard Marine) noticed on an invoice that container GLDU 960640-6 was carrying non-hazardous as well as hazardous cargo (UN 1044 Fire Extinguishers). The container was on terminal grounds at the time we (Seaboard Marine) notice that undeclared hazardous cargoes had been loaded. We immediately placed a HOLD on the container and prohibited future movement. The shipper was asked to provide the proper documentation describing all the hazardous materials inside of the container. The same day, upon receipt, review and acceptance of the shipping papers, the container was placarded accordingly and afterward released for transportation

column168: Driver was southbound on I-5 going up a steep grade.  Another driver passing our driver indicated our driver had a problem. Our driver pulled into rest area and saw product dripping from the trailer by the rear tires.  Our insurance company was called and they had an independent adjuster immediately go to the scene.  Our driver positioned the truck and trailer on level ground and the leak stopped. We transferred the load to another trailer without further incident.
column169: It appears that as our driver was going up the steep grade, the product moved towards the rear of the trailer, got into the rear clean-out pipe.  the clean-out cap leaked which is what our driver saw when he pulled over.  When we had the trailer purged, cleaned an inspected the cargo tank facility could not find anything wrong.  They though maybe the clean-out cap was a little loose, or possibly the threads were damaged or the clean-out cap itself was deformed so they replaced the clean-out cap.    We have instructed our drivers to double check the clean-out caps when picking up a trailer at a tank wash and insure the caps are tight and free from movement.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred. During routine inspection of trailer at truck stop, a leak was discovered on back of trailer. Site was secured, and SWS Environmental was dispatched to perform the cleanup. Upon arrival on site, free product was noted on back of trailer tailgate, but no leak was detected inside trailer. SWS Environmental applied absorbent material and pads to the trailer floor, as a precaution, and followed the RRTS, Inc. trailer to their facility in Mt. Joliet, TN. Upon arrival, SWS Environmental proceeded to offload the trailer to determine cause of release. One (1) 15-gallon drum of free product was discovered. Apparently, a pinhole leak in bottom of drum, resulted in loss of contents from the damaged drum. Free product was contained to the trailer floor, which was recovered and containerized into one (1) 55 gallon recovery drum, pending disposal in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations. The damaged drum was also over packed into a recovery drum, pending disposition. There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Roadrunner Transportation Services, Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

column168: 04:30 hours on November 29, 2014, a Kansas City Southern Railway (KCS) employee discovered a residue tank car, UTLX 673257, leaking Ethylene Glycol in the Beaumont, TX Yard. All concerned were notified. KCS dispatched a hazmat responder. Upon arrival the responder determined that the lading was leaking from the BOV . The bottom outlet valve handle was not pinned or secured and was approximately one-quarter open. The two (2) inch plug in the bottom outlet cap was not tool tight. The responder closed the bottom outlet valve and pinned the handle. The two (2) inch plug was removed, thread sealant was applied and the plug was tool tightened. Security seal 456712 was applied to the bottom outlet valve handle. The spilled product was cleaned up to prevent a slipping hazard for yard workers.     File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure issues such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.     (Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Steve McNealy, KCS Railway, P.O. Box 219335, Kansas City, MO 64121. The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: 5 year inspection was done October of 2012. Driver was heading north on I45 to Waxahachie, Tx with a load from HAT Ammonia in Houston, Tx when driver noticed the relief valve was weeping. Luck be that our field service tech was going south and turned around to follow the driver. Service tech started smelling ammonia, so after discussions with upper management we made the decision to find a safe haven off the interstate to park and put a plan into action. Driver called 911 and I called NRC and Chemtrec to report and let them know we had a plan in place and was executing it. We arrived approx. 9 pm witha empty ammonia trailer and a field service van with equipment to transfer product from leaking trailer to good trailer. All went as planned with no issues. We had one person from the sheriffs department there to help with traffic. After our investigation the next day, looks like baffle broke inside and bent the PRV. Trailer is in shop for repairs.
column169: Discussed with our Safety and Regulatory Affairs department on maybe checking baffles yearly. Retrain plant and drivers to check for any unusual noises that might be coming from inside tank.

column168: ON NOVEMBER 21. 2014 A TANKER TRUCK FROM THE LOGAN CITY MAINTENANCE SHOPS BEGAN PUMPING USED OIL FROM A 2000 GALLON DOUBLE WALLED STATIONARY TANK LOCATED EAST OF THE LANDFILL AND WEST OF THE GREEN WASTE FACILITY. THE TANKER TRUCK HAS TWO COMPARTMENTS. THE OPERATOR OF THE TANKER TRUCK WAS PUMPING OIL INTO THE FRONT COMPARTMENT AND HAD NEGLECTED TO CLOSE A VALVE ON THE BACK COMPARTMENT. THE BACK COMPARTMENT OF THE TANKER OVERFILLED AND FLOWED OUT OF THE TANKER TRUCK ONTO THE GROUND AND THEN TOWARDS A DITCH AT THE ROADWAY TO THE WEST. IT IS ESTIMATED THAT ABOUT 250 GALLONS OF OIL WERE LOST ONTO THE GROUND. OUR INVESTIGATION OF THE INCIDENT CONCLUDED THAT THE TANKER OPERATOR WAS INATTENTIVE AND THAT HE SHOULD HAVE CAUGHT THE SPILL VERY EARLY ALLOWING LITTLE TO HIT THE GROUND. THE DISCHARGED OIL DID NOT REACH NAVIGABLE WATERS OR ANY STANDING WATER.
column169: THE 2000 GALLON USED OIL STORAGE TANK WAS COMPLETELY EMPTIED BY NOVEMBER 26, 2014. THE PLAN IS TO REMOVE THE TANK FROM THE LANDFILL TO ELIMINATE FURTHER SPILLS, A LANDFILL INSPECTOR WILL MONITOR ALL OTHER USED OIL TRANSFERS THAT OCCUR WITH PRIVATE OR PUBLIC CARRIERS. TRAINING REGARDING STAYING AT THE SITE OF THE TRANSFER WILL OCCUR FOR LANDFILL EMPLOYEES.

column17: AmeriGas Propane LP dba Propane Transport International
column168: Semi-transport was in the process of transferring liquid propane from the tank vehicle into an underground storage when a stainless steel flex line burst. The transport driver ran to the nearest post and hit the plant emergency stop button. Next he ran to the cab of the tractor and turned off the key switch which stopped the motor of the tractor then ran to the business office and shut off the main electric breaker for the property. After this action, he then ran through the forming gas cloud along a paved driveway to an business which was occupied with individuals who were in fitness classes and alerted the persons to potential danger. When he entered the building, the gas vapors contacted an ignition source and the vapors flashed into a fire ball. The remaining escaping product was consumed by the fire but the radiated heat from the fire and the some exposure during the flash fire resulted in neighboring buildings igniting and burning. The persons in the fitness center escaped through a broken window which was facing away from the fire scene. No persons reported any injuries from the explosion or fire.
column169: Identify the reason as the failure of the stainless steel flex line.

column168: ON NOVEMBER 7, 2014 A RELEASE OF HAZARDOUS WASTE FILTER CAKE OCCURRED DURING THE PROCESS OF EXHANGING THE ROLLOFF BIN FROM BENEATH THE FILTER PRESS. THE ACTIVITY REQUIRED THAT A STRAIGHT TRUCK PULL THE FULL BIN FROM BENEATH THE PRESS, MOVE IT OUT OF THE WAY, PLACE IT BACK ON THE GROUND, AND THEN PLACE A NEW EMPTY BIN BENEATH THE PRESS. ONCE THE EMPTY CONTAINER HAS BEEN PLACED BENEATH THE PRESS, THE DRIVER AND GLOBALFOUNDRIES PERSONNEL PREPARE THE FULL BIN FOR SHIPMENT WHILE THE CONTAINER IS ON THE GROUND (INSPECTION, CONVER, PLACARDS, ETC.). THE DRIVER THEN LOADS THE BIN AND SECURES IT TO THE TRUCK. ONCE IT IS SECURE, GLOBALFOUNDRIES PERSONNEL WILL INSPECT THE TRUCK AND SIGN THE SHIPPER PAPARWORK TO RELEASE THE TRUCK.     THE RELEASE OCCURRED BECUASE MATERIAL SLOGHED OVER THE BACK END OF THE BIN AS THE STRAIGHT TRUCK OPERATOR WAS LOWERING THE BIN BACK TO THE GROUND SO THAT AN EMPTY BIN COULD BE PLACED BENEATH THE PRESS. THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE WAS THAT THE MATERIAL HAD AN UNACCEPTABLE AMOUNT OF MOISTURE AND HAD NOT BEEN APPROPRIATELY STABILIZED. GLOBALFOUONDRIES PERSONNEL REPORTED THAT A PREVIOUS CLEANING ACTIVITY HAD LED TO WATER ACCUMULATING IN THE BIN. PERSONNEL ATTEMPTED TO DEWATER THE BIN PRIOR TO REMOVAL, BUT HAD REMOVED A SUFFICIENT AMOUNT MOISTURE.    THE GLOBALFOUNDRIES ONSITE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM (ERT) RESPONDED IMMEDIATELY TO CONTAIN THE RELEASE. THE FLOW OF MATERIAL HAD ALREADY BEEN STOPPED BY RAISING THE CONTAINER BACK ONTO THE TRUCK. THE ERT IMMEDIATELY BLOCKED THE STORM DRAIN USING A CATCH BASIN COVER AND ABSORBENT BOOMS/PADS TO PREVENT ADDITIONAL MATERIAL FROM SEEPING INTO THE STRUCTURE.    THE GLOBALFOUNDRIES ERT RESPONSE TRAILER WAS MOBILIZED TO THE SCENE AND THE INCIDENT COMMAND SYSTEM (ICS) WAS IMPLEMENTED TO BEGIN THE CLEANUP AND DECON OF THE AREA. ERT PERSONNEL REMOVED THE BULK OF THE MATERIAL MANUALLY AND PLACED INTO DRUMS. THE IMPACTED GRAVEL AREA WAS SCRAPPED AND SCOURED TO REMOVE ALL VISIBLY IMPACTED MATERIAL. THE ASPHALT AREA WAS THEN FURTHER CLEANED USING SPEEDIE-DRI. SPEEDIE-DRI WAS THE REMOVED AND DRUMMED AS WELL.    THERE ARE NO HAZARDOUS CHARACTERISTICS (IGNITABILITY, REACTIVITY, TOXICITY, OR CORROSIVITY) ASSOCIATED WITH THIS SLUDGE. HOWEVER, DUE TO THE FACT THAT THIS SLUDGE IS GENERATED FROM THE TREATMENT OF ELECTROPLATING WASTEWATERS, THIS MATERIAL CARRIES THE F006 HAZARDOUS WASTE CODE.
column169: THE FOLLOWING ACITONS WILL BE TAKEN BY GLOBALFOUNDRIES TO PREVENT RECURRENCE:    * MAINTENANCE PROCEDURES WILL BE REVISED TO EMPHASIZE CONTROLS TO PREVENT MOISTURE FROM ENTERING THE ROLLOFF;  * GLOBALFOUNDRIES PERSONNEL WILL INSPECT THE ROLLOFF BIN FOR EVIDENCE OF MOISTURE PRIOR TO REMOVAL FROM BENEATH THE FILTER PRESS; AND  * NO ROLLOFF BINS WITH EVIDENCE OF EXCESSIVE MOISTURE WILL BE REMOVED FROM BENEATH THE FILTER PRESS UNTIL THE MATERIAL HAS BEEN APPROPRIATELY STABILIZED.

column168: CN transportation department employee noted liquid coming from tank car UTLX 201093 (L / Methanol, UN1230) during switching operations at the CN Mays Yard, Harahan, LA. All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated. CN's response team responded noting liquid appeared to be coming from the combination housing.  The combination housing was opened and liquid was observed coming from the liquid valve plug.  The plug was checked and found to be less than tool tight.  The plug was removed, teflon sealant tape was applied, and re-installed tool tight.  The leak was secured, tank car was released for movement.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: THE TIDEPORT DRIVER WAS MAKING A LEFT HAND TURN FROM HWY 359 ONTO THE ON RAMP OF HWY 37 SOUTH THE DRIVER TOOK THE TURN AT A TOO HIGH RATE OF SPEED (APPROX 35 MPH) AND THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER ROLLED ONTO THEIR RIGHT SIDE. THE IMPACT OF THE ROLLOVER CAUSE A LEAK FORM THE DOME LIND OF TRAILER. MATHIS FIRE DEPT. ARRIVED IN ABOUT 15 MIN AND PUT A TUB UNDER THE LEAK TO CAPTURE THE PRODUCT THAT WAS LEAKING OUT. TIDEPORT EMPLOYEES ATTEMTPED TO TIGHTEN THE DOME LID, BUT IT WAS ALREADY TIGHT. SWS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES WERE CALLED OUT BY TIDEPORT TO TRANSFER THE PRODUCT OUT OF THE DAMAGED UNIT ONTO ANOTHER TIDEPORT VEHICLE. SWS THEN HANDLED THE REMEDIATION AND CLEAN UP OF THE AREA.
column169: TIDEPORT HELD A SAFETY MEETING FOR ALL DRIVERS ON DEC 17, 2014. DURING THAT MEETING THE ACCIDENT WAS REVIEWED AND ALL DRIVERS WERE REMINDED TO SLOW DOWN THROUGH ALL CURVES AND TURNS DURING THE MEETING WE ALSO VIEWED THE VIDEO "ROLLOVER" BY FMCSA AND PHMSA.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS LOADING PRODUCT ONTO LYKINS TRAILER 3022 AT LOAD ARM #11 AT THE MARATHON TERMINAL IN COVINGTON, KY ON NOVEMBER 25, 2014 AT OR AROUND 4:30 AM. OUR DRIVER INITIALLY REPORTED THAT HE HAD SET THE METER FOR 3400 GALLONS OF GASOLINE FOR HIS INTENDED COMPARTMENT. AS THE METER REACHED 2500 GALLONS, THE LOAD ARM SHUT OFF AND AN ERROR MESSAGE WAS PRODUCED ON THE MONITORING  SCREEN. THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO COAX AN ADDITIONAL 128 GALLONS FROM THE LOAD ARM BEFORE IT SHUT OFF A SECOND TIME. THE DRIVER THEN REPORTED THE ISSUE TO THE OPERATOR AT THE LOCAL OFFICE. THE OPERATOR RESET THE LOAD ARM, AND ANOTHER 40 GALLONS WAS PUMPED ONTO OUR TRAILER BEFORE SHUTTING OFF AGAIN. THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO RESTART THE LOAD ARM, AND AN ADDITIONAL 700 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS PUMPED ON TO OUR TRAILER. AFTER THE METER PASSED 700, GASOLINE BEGAN TO SPRAY FROM THE TOP OF THE TRAILER. THE LOAD ARM SHUT ITSELF OFF SHORTLY BEFORE RESUMING PUMPING PRODUCT ONTO THE TRAILER.  50 GALLONS WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE LOADING BAY, WHILE AS ESTIMATED 30 GALLONS ESCAPED ONTO THE BLACKTOP OUTSIDE OF THE BAY ITSELF. OUR DRIVER IMMEDIATELY REPORTED THE SPILL TO THE OPERATOR, WHO RESPONDED BY BRINGING SPILL PADS TO CONTAIN THE OVERFLOW. THE OPERATOR CAME BACK WITH OIL DRY, AND PLACED A RUBBER MAT OVER A NEARBY DRAIN. AT APPROXIMATELY 6:00 AM, THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. CLEAN HARBOR, A REMEDIATION COMPANY, WAS THEN CONTACTED TO PROCEED WITH THE CLEAN-UP OPERATION. THE TERMINAL MANAGER ARRIVED ON SCENE AT OR AROUND 6:30 AM, AND THE BULK OF THE TERMINAL STAFF ARRIVED AT 8:00 AM, AS WELL AS CLEAN HARBOR. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT REMAINED ON-SCENE UNTIL 11:00 AM, AND CLEAN HARBOR COMPLETED REMEDIATION AT APPROXIMATELY 12:00 PM. MARATHON THEN INITIATED A PUMP-OFF OF OUR OVERFILLED COMPARTMENT AT 12:30 PM.  AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT, NO BILL OF LADING WAS GENERATED BY MARATHON.  THE RACK WAS OFFLINE FROM THE ESTIMATED TIME OF SPILL (5:00 AM) UNTIL 12:00 PM.  SUBSEQUENT INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE SENSOR ON THE AFFECTED COMPARTMENT HAD BEEN BYPASSED, BUT DID NOT REVEAL THE EXACT OCCURRENCE AS TO WHEN THE SENSOR WAS BYPASSED PRIOR TO THE INCIDENT.
column169: AS NOTED IN OUR RESPONSE TO PART VI, A FAULT OCCURRED WHEN A SENSOR CONNECTED TO THE SCULLY WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE BEEN BYPASSED IN OUR SUBSEQUENT INVESTIGATION.  NONE OF OUR VEHICLE MAINTENANCE PERSONNEL REPORTED TAKING SUCH ACTIONS. ALL VEHICLE MAINTENANCE PERSONNEL HAVE BEEN NOTIFIED TO BE ON ALERT FOR ANY OTHER MODIFICATIONS TO THE TRAILER UNITS THAT COULD POTENTIALLY CAUSE PRODUCT TO OVERFLOW DURING LOADING. WE MAINTAIN THAT OUR PERSONNEL DID NOT CAUSE OR CONTRIBUTE TO THE ERROR DISCOVERED IN TRAILER 3022.    ALTHOUGH MULTIPLE COMPANY DRIVERS HAVE REPORTED ISSUES WITH LOAD ARM #11 AT MARATHON TERMINAL IN COVINGTON, MARATHON HAS NOT PUBLISHED ANY SUCH FINDINGS.  LYKINS TRANSPORTATION DRIVERS HAVE BEEN REMINDED TO BE ON ALERT FOR ANY SUCH ANOMALIES WHILE LOADING AT OTHER TERMINALS SINCE THIS INCIDENT OCCURRED. OUR DRIVER ASSISTED IN SECURING THE SCENE, AND THE TERMINAL REQUISITIONED ALL NECESSARY PERSONNEL TO COMPLETE THEIR REMEDIATION PROCEDURE. THE TERMINAL WAS CLOSED FOR SEVEN HOURS, BUT NO PRODUCT ESCAPED INTO ANY DRAIN PIPES, SEWER OR STORM LINES, OR NEARBY GRASSLANDS.

column168: IN NOVEMBER 17,2014 AN ORDER WAS PLACED BY MRS. WALKER FOR 150 GALLONS OF HEATING OIL FOR THEIR HOME ON KINSMAN ROAD. A DRIVER THAT WAS FAMILIAR WITH THIS RESIDENCE MADE THE DELIVERY ON NOVEMBER 18, 2014 AROUND NOON. HE PUT THE ORDER OF 150 GALLONS OF HEATING OIL TANK THAT HAD NOT BEEN USED FOR MANY YEARS BECAUSE IT WAS RUSTED OUT ON BOTTOM. THE CORRECT TANK WAS AN UNDERGROUND TANK NEARBY. NEITHER WERE MARKED.  AT 6PM ON THE DAY OF DELIVERY WAS MADE AND PUT INTO THE CORRECT TANK. THE INCIDENT WAS INVESTIGATED BY MANAGEMENT TO VERIFY DETAILS. BBU ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CALLED IN FOR CLEAN UP OF RELEASE. CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS EXCAVATED AND REMOVED FROM SITE.  DRAINS IN BASEMENT WERE PUMPED OUT.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1:00 AM ON NOVEMBER 1, A CHEMTRADE OPERATIONS EMPLOYEE (EMPLOYEE) ARRIVED AT THE WISCONSIN RAPIDS, WI ALUMINUM SULFATE (ALUM) PRODUCTION FACILITY (PLANT)TO BEGIN HIS SHIFT. THE EMPLOYEE'S PLAN FOR THAT DAY WAS TO PUMP A BATCH OF ALUM FORM A MIX TANK OVER TO THE STORAGE TANK AND DELIVER A LOAD OF SULFURIC ACID. THE ACT OF TRANSFERRING ALUM INVOLVES A SERIES OF WATER DILUTIONS FOLLOWED BY QUALITY CHECKS. THE EMPLOYEE PLANNED TO PERFORM THESE TASKS WHILE LOADING ACID INTO HIS TANKER. AFTER ALUM WAS PUMPED TO STORAGE, THE TANK TRUCK WAS PULLED UNDER THE LOADING RACK AND THE NECESSARY HOSE CONNECTION MADE. THE LOADING SYSTEM IS AUTOMATIC, MEANING FILLING IS STOPPED WHEN A PRE-DETERMINED AMOUNT OF ACID IS LOADED. THE DESIRED AMOUNT WAS MANUALLY ENTERED AND THE ACID PUMPING PROCESS INITIATED. DURING ACID FILLING, THE EMPLOYEE BEGAN DILUTING THE ALUM TO SHIPPING STRENGTH. WHEN THE ACID FILLING PROCESS STOPPED, THE EMPLOYEE SHUT THE LOADING VALVE, REMOVED THE HOSE, AND CLOSED THE TANK DOME LID. HOWEVER AS A CRITICAL ALUM DILUTION STEP WAS OCCURRING AT THE SAME TIME, HE IMMEDIATELY TENDS TO IT, NEGLECTING TO SECURE THE DOME.    AT APPROXIMATELY 3:10 AM , THE NECESSARY PAPERWORK IS COMPLETED AND COMPILED, THE EMPLOYEE CLIMBS INTO THE TRUCK TO BEGIN THE DELIVERY. APPROXIMATELY 1.2 MILES INTO THE DRIVE, THE EMPLOYEE NOTICES IN HIS REARVIEW MIRROR LIQUID SPLASHING DOWN FROM THE TOP OF THE TANKER. THE TRUCK IS PULLED TO A SAFE STOP AND THE ISSUE IS CONFIRMED; SULFURIC ACID HAD LEAKED OUT OF THE UNSECURED TOP DOME AND WAS BEING DISCHARGED ALONG THE ROAD.  THE AMOUNT RELEASED IS ESTIMATED TO BE 3O GALLONS. AT APPROXIMATELY 4:15 AM, 1 HOUR AFTER THE RELEASE IS DISCOVERED, THE WISCONSIN RAPIDS FIRE DEPARTMENT (FIRE DEPT) ARRIVES ON THE SCENE. THEY PLACE SPILL ABSORBENTS IN FRONT OF THE NEARBY STORM DRAIN APPROXIMATELY 200 FEET FROM THE TRUCK.  AT APPROXIMATELY THE SAME TIME, THE WISCONSIN RAPIDS POLICE DEPARTMENT (POLICE) BEGINS CLOSING OFF 1 LANE OF ROAD ALONG THE ENTIRE LENGTH OF THE SPILL.    PLANT SUPERVISION (SUPERVISOR) ARRIVES AND MEETS WITH THE FIRE CHIEF, WHO IS ACTING AS INCIDENT COMMANDER (IC) TO DISCUSS CLEANUP OPTIONS. THE SUPERVISOR OFFERS TO RETRIEVE SODA ASH FROM THE PLANT TO SPREAD ON THE AFFECTED ROADWAY. THE IC HAS CONCERNS ABOUT DAMAGING THE ROAD AND AFTER CONSULTATION WITH HIS INTERNAL SPILL TEAM, DECIDES TO UTILIZE FLOOR DRY INSTEAD. SOON AFTER, ALL OF THE CITY STOCK IS USED AND IT BECOMES NECESSARY TO OBTAIN 200 BAGS FROM A LOCAL AUTO SUPPLY STORE TO COMPLETELY COVER THE IMPACTED AREA.    THERE IS ENOUGH UNCERTAINTY REGARDING THE SCOPE OF THE SPILL TO WARRANT REGULATORY NOTIFICATIONS AND A CALL TO OUTSIDE CLEANUP ASSISTANCE. THE ENVIRONMENTAL REP CALLS THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER FOLLOWED BY THE WISCONSIN SPILL HOTLINE. RELEASED AMOUNT IS GIVEN AS A RANGE OF 30-100 GALLONS, POSSIBLE ABOVE THE RQ, WITH MOST CONFINED TO THE ROADWAY.  THE REGULATORY AUTHORITIES ACCEPT THE RANGE GIVE, AS LONG AS A FOLLOW UP NOTIFICATION IS GIVEN
column169: ON MONDAY, FOLLOW UP IS MADE TO ALL REGULATORY AGENCIES.  A LIST OF RELEVANT CORRECTION ACTIONS ARE DEVELOPED AND ASSIGNED FOR COMPLETION.  CORRECTIVE ACTIONS RELEVANT TO THIS REPORT ARE AN IMPROVEMENT TO EMPLOYEE TRAINING PROGRAMS AND LOADING/UNLOADING PROTOCOLS.

column168: OUR TRACTOR-TRAILER WAS LOADED WITH 10,500 GALLONS OF ETHANOL RECEIVED FROM THE GLOBAL TERMINAL IN THE PORT OF ALBANY, NY FOR DELIVERY TO THE EXXONMOBIL TERMINAL IN SPRINGFIELD, MA. THE TRUCK HAD PASSED THRU THE TOLLBOOTH A T I90 B1 NEAR NASSAU, NY AND WAS ENTERING THE ON-RAMP TO I90 EAST. THIS RAMP IS A DOWNWARD SWEEPING RIGHT TURN. IT APPEARS OUR DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO NEGOTIATE THE CURVE AT TOO HIGH A SPEED. THE TRUCK WENT OFF THE LEFT SHOULDER, ROLLED 1.5 TIMES COMING TO REST WITH THE TRACTOR ON THE GRASS ALONG I90 EAST AND THE TRAILER EXTENDING ONTO I90 EAST. OUR DRIVER FREED HIMSELF FROM THE VEHICLE AND WAS TREATED AND RELEASED THE SAME DAY AT ALBANY MEDICAL CENTER WITH LACERATIONS AND CONTUSIONS. INTERSTATE 90 WAS SHUT DOWN FROM APPROXIMATELY 9:00 A.M. TO 6:30 P.M. ON 11/29/2014. AN ESTIMATED 7500 GALLONS OF ETHANOL WAS RECOVERED FROM OUR OVERTURNED TRAILER. THE REMAINING SPILLED PRODUCT WAS RECOVERED BY VACUUM TRUCKS THAT WERE CALLED IN RESPONSE TO THE ACCIDENT. AT THIS TIME, THERE DOES NOT APPEAR TO BE ANY LASTING ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE. THE ETHANOL THAT DID LEAK FROM OUR TRUCK APPEARED TO COME FROM A PUNCTURE WOUND NEAR COMPARTMENT #4 RECEIVED WHILE THE TRAILER ROLLED OVER. NONE OF THE DOME COVERS OR BOTTOM SUMP VALVES FAILED.
